PROBLEM 3 — FIBONACCI
Fibonacci sequence: 0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, ...
  fib(0) = 0
  fib(1) = 1
  fib(n) = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2)   for n > 1
    def fib(n):
        if n <= 1:              # base case
            return n
        return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2)
    for i in range(6):
        print(fib(i))
Output: 0 1 1 2 3 5
Tree of calls for fib(4):
             fib(4)
           /        \
        fib(3)      fib(2)
        /    \       /    \
    fib(2) fib(1) fib(1) fib(0)
    /    \
 fib(1) fib(0)
Notice: fib(2) is calculated TWICE.
This is called overlapping subproblems — this is why
Dynamic Programming (DP) becomes important for Fibonacci
at large n. (Covered in later sessions.)
Time Complexity of naive recursion: O(2^n)
